Web Components

JavaScript

Web Development

Drupal

9 min read
1 hour ago

--

In the previous article, we explored Web Components as the browser’s native component model and saw how Custom Elements, Shadow DOM, Slots, lifecycle callbacks, attributes and Custom Events work together.
Now let’s build one.
Press enter or click to view image in full size

In this article, we’ll create a reusable <counter-button> Web Component from scratch, step by step, following the same path the browser takes when it creates and manages a component.
By the end, we’ll have a standalone ES Module and a small demo app that uses it like any other frontend project. The same component could also be used in a plain HTML page, a Drupal site or a component library.
The goal is not just to build a button that counts, but to see how each browser feature helps create a reusable component.

Starting with an Empty Project
We’ll keep the project structure simple and separate the reusable component from the application that consumes it.
counter-button/
│
├── src/
│ ├── counter-button.js
│ └── index.js
│
├── demo/
│ ├── index.html
│ ├── app.js
│ └── styles.css
│
└── package.jsonThe src directory contains our Web Component, while the demo directory acts as a consumer application.
This separation is intentional. A Web Component should be developed independently of the application that uses it. Whether the consumer is a plain HTML page, a Drupal site or a React application, the component should behave the same.
As we build the component, we’ll use the demo application to verify that it works, just as another application would consume it.
Note: Since this project uses ES Modules, you’ll need to serve the demo files over HTTP (for example, using VS Code Live Server or a simple local web server). Opening index.html directly from the filesystem (file://) will result in module loading errors.

Teaching the Browser a New HTML Element
Let’s begin with the smallest possible Web Component.
// src/counter-button.jsexport class CounterButton extends HTMLElement {
}
Like any HTML element, our component extends HTMLElement. At this point, it's just a JavaScript class. The browser still doesn't know that it should create this class when it encounters a <counter-button> element.
To teach the browser about our new element, we register it with the Custom Element Registry.
customElements.define("counter-button", CounterButton);That’s all it takes. The browser now knows that whenever it encounters <counter-button>, it should create an instance of the CounterButton class.
To make the component available to consumers, we’ll export it from a single entry point.
// src/index.jsimport "./counter-button.js";
Now let’s use it in our demo application.
// demo/app.jsimport "../src/index.js";
<!-- demo/index.html --><!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
<meta charset="UTF-8">
<meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
<title>Counter Button Demo</title>
</head>
<body>
<!-- Our web component -->
<counter-button></counter-button>
<!-- Scripts to import the js bundle -->
<script type="module" src="./app.js"></script>
</body>
</html>
If you open the page, nothing appears yet, which is exactly what we expect. The browser knows about the element now, so the next step is to give it something to render.

Rendering Our First Component
With our component registered and the demo application importing it, the browser can now upgrade the <counter-button> element into an instance of our CounterButton class. The only thing missing is something to render.
To render something, we’ll use the connectedCallback() lifecycle method. The browser calls this method when the component is added to the document, which makes it a good place for the initial markup.
// src/counter-button.jsexport class CounterButton extends HTMLElement {
connectedCallback() {
this.innerHTML = `
<button>Count: 0</button>
`;
}
}
customElements.define("counter-button", CounterButton);
Refresh the page, and you’ll see your first Web Component.
This works, but the button is rendered directly into the component’s DOM. That means its structure and styles are exposed to the rest of the application.
Let’s move the implementation into a Shadow DOM and give the component its own private DOM tree.

Encapsulating the Component with Shadow DOM
Rendering directly into the component works, but it has one drawback: the component’s internal HTML becomes part of the page’s DOM. That means application styles can affect the component, and the component’s styles can affect the application.
To avoid this, we’ll create a Shadow DOM and render everything inside it. Update the connectedCallback() as below
connectedCallback() {
this.attachShadow({ mode: "open" });
this.shadowRoot.innerHTML = `
<button>Count: 0</button>
`;
}The only new line is:
this.attachShadow({ mode: "open" });Note: This example uses mode: "open" so the Shadow Root is accessible via element.shadowRoot, making development and debugging easier. The browser also supports mode: "closed", which keeps the Shadow Root inaccessible from external JavaScript.
This creates a Shadow Root — a private DOM tree attached to our <counter-button> element. Instead of rendering into the page's DOM, we now render into this.shadowRoot.
If you refresh the page, it will look exactly the same.
Although nothing has changed visually, the component’s implementation is now encapsulated. Its internal HTML no longer lives in the page’s DOM, laying the foundation for scoped styles, private implementation and a clean public API.
Earlier, the Element’s DOM tree looked like:
Now, it is encapsulated in a Shadow DOM:
Next, we’ll separate rendering into its own render() method so the component can update its UI whenever its state changes.

Separating Rendering from Component Logic
Our component currently renders its HTML directly inside connectedCallback(). This works for a simple example, but as the component grows, we'll need to render it more than once. For example, when its state or configuration changes.
A common pattern is to move the rendering logic into a dedicated render() method.
// src/counter-button.jsexport class CounterButton extends HTMLElement {
connectedCallback() {
this.attachShadow({ mode: "open" });
this.render();
}
render() {
this.shadowRoot.innerHTML = `
<button>Count: 0</button>
`;
}
}
customElements.define("counter-button", CounterButton);
The behavior hasn’t changed, but the component is now better structured. connectedCallback() is responsible for initializing the component, while render() is responsible for updating the user interface.
This separation becomes increasingly valuable as we add features. Instead of modifying the DOM in multiple places, we’ll simply update the component’s state and call render() whenever the UI needs to be refreshed.
Next, we’ll introduce the component’s first piece of state: the current count and make the button respond to user interaction.

Adding State and User Interaction
Let’s make the button interactive by giving the component its own state.
First, initialize a count property in the constructor.
constructor() {
super();
this.count = Number(this.getAttribute("count")) || 0;
}Next, update the render() method to display the current value.
<button>Count: ${this.count}</button>Finally, in the render() method, update the click handler to increment the count and re-render the component whenever the button is clicked.
this.shadowRoot
.querySelector("button")
.addEventListener("click", () => {
this.count++;
this.render();
});Refresh the page and click the button.
The component now maintains its own state and updates its interface whenever that state changes.
Notice that count is currently an internal JavaScript property. Consumers can't configure it yet as it always start from zero.
Next, we'll expose count as a public attribute so the component can be configured directly from HTML.

Making the Component Configurable
Currently, consumers have no way to configure count property. Let’s expose it as an HTML attribute.
First, tell the browser that our component wants to observe changes to the count attribute by adding below method to class CounterButton.
static get observedAttributes() {
return ["count"];
}Whenever the count attribute changes, the browser invokes attributeChangedCallback(). So, read the count attribute value inside this method and re-render.
attributeChangedCallback(name, oldValue, newValue) {
if (name === "count") {
this.count = Number(newValue); if (this.shadowRoot) {
this.render();
}
}
}
Why don’t we always call render() until shadowRoot is created?
When the browser creates <counter-button count="5">, it invokes attributeChangedCallback() before connectedCallback(). At that point, the Shadow DOM hasn't been created yet, so this.shadowRoot is still null. We therefore render only after the component has been connected to the document.
Now the component can be configured directly from HTML. Suppose we have placed 2 counter-button elements on a page,
<counter-button count="5"></counter-button><counter-button count="10"></counter-button>Each instance maintains its own state, but starts with a different initial value Count:5 and Count:5 respectively.
This is the same pattern used by native HTML elements. Just as an <input> is configured with attributes like type or placeholder, our component exposes count as part of its public API.
Next, we’ll allow the application to react whenever the counter changes by dispatching a custom event.

Communicating with Custom Events
Our component is now configurable, but it still works in isolation. When the count changes, the application has no way of knowing about it.
Instead of exposing internal implementation details, Web Components communicate through Custom Events.
After incrementing the count in button’s click handler in render()method, dispatch an event with the updated value.
this.dispatchEvent(
new CustomEvent("counter-changed", {
detail: {
count: this.count
}
})
);The application can now listens for this event like it would for any native browser event.
Add below snippet to demo/app.js or try it out in Browser’s console
const counter = document.querySelector("counter-button");counter.addEventListener("counter-changed", (event) => {
console.log(`Current count: ${event.detail.count}`);
});
The component remains a black box. The application doesn’t need to know about the button inside the Shadow DOM; it simply listens for a meaningful event exposed through the component’s public API.
Now, let’s package the component as a standalone ES Module and see how it can be consumed by another application.

Packaging the Component
So far, we’ve been importing the component directly from the source code. That’s convenient during development, but applications typically consume a bundled JavaScript module instead.
Let’s create a distributable bundle.
Step 1: Configure the package
Create a package.json file.
{
"name": "@your-org/counter-button",
"version": "1.0.0",
"type": "module",
"main": "./dist/counter-button.js",
"exports": {
".": "./dist/counter-button.js"
},
"scripts": {
"build": "esbuild src/index.js --bundle --format=esm --outfile=dist/counter-button.js"
},
"devDependencies": {
"esbuild": "^0.25.0"
}
}Install the dependencies.
npm installStep 2: Build the bundle
Run the build script.
npm run buildThis produces a distributable ES Module.
counter-button/
├── dist/
│ └── counter-button.js
├── src/
├── demo/
└── package.jsonAt this point, your component is ready to be reused by any application.
Publishing to npm
If you want to share the component publicly or within your organization, simply publish the package using npm publish
Applications can then install it using:
npm install @your-org/counter-button

Using the Component in Drupal
We’ll use the bundled module we just created.
Copy dist/counter-button.js into your Drupal module or theme.
my_module/
├── js/
│ └── counter-button.js
├── my_module.libraries.yml
└── templates/Expose the module through a libr
